<td>3.4× baseline</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>5,000 words, low fact density (1:250)</td>
<td>1.0× baseline</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>5,000 words, high fact density (1:80)</td>
<td>4.1× baseline</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>2,500 words, low fact density (1:250)</td>
<td>0.6× baseline</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
<p>A 2,500-word article with high fact density outperforms a 5,000-word article with low fact density by <strong>3.4×</strong>. Length helps only when density is already high. A 5,000-word article with high fact density performs best overall at 4.1×, but the density component drives most of that lift.</p>
<div class="table-wrap"><table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Word Count</th>
